caption: This church is absolutely beautiful. If you're looking to attend Latin mass while in Paris you will be able to do so here, and the information on their website is up-to-date. They also do adoration on Thursday evenings after mass.

I went to Saint Eugene Sainte Cecile church in Montmartre since I read somewhere that their Sunday High Mass is spectacular - an ‚ÄúExtraordinary Form of the Roman Rite‚Äù.  90 minutes, priest, 6 sub priests, 4 altar boys, organist and choir.  Church is neo-gothic style/decor and the ‚Äúchoir is one of the best in France.‚Äú  Lots of singing and rituals.  Church itself was very interesting decor - built in 1854/55 when medieval art was rediscovered and neo-gothic churches were built across the country.  Metal framework was used which was painted in red, green and gold with embellishments; dark wood carved railings etc.  However, I didn‚Äôt feel right looking around too much due to the solemnity and because everyone else was there for spiritual reasons.

The facade is not the most enticing or attractive but the ‚Äúhistorical monument‚Äù sign took me by surprise. Wow, superb interior. I was careful not to make any noise because the parishioners were immersed in their prayers. Beautiful place of worship

One of the most beautiful churches in Paris. If the exterior does not invite a visit, no bell tower, in a small street with little traffic, the interior is exceptional with its colors, warmth, and magnificent stained glass windows. You have to take a detour from the nearby Grands Boulevards to discover this little gem.

Magnificent church, a true architectural marvel with its exceptional liturgical furniture and endless ornaments. The divine is even more present thanks to this beauty that surrounds us, so don't hesitate to stop by!! üôÇ

In neo-Gothic style, it was built in the mid-19th century. However, being located just opposite the Conservatory of Music and Dance already present, in order not to disturb the students, it was decided that this church would not have a bell tower! After this original discovery, the surprise continues inside. We quickly notice the numerous slender columns painted in cast iron. It is the first building built with these materials. The finesse of these columns gives an impression of lightness and grandeur.¬†The eye is quickly caught by the light provided by the numerous stained glass windows on either side. The choir, lit by 3 large windows, the paintings, the side chapels, the aisles, the pulpit, the statues, etc... everything contributes to the beauty of the place. The marriage of Jules Verne was celebrated in this church which also offers masses in Latin, and even ‚ÄúGregorian vespers‚Äù on Sundays! Finally, this original church without a bell tower has been listed as a Historic Monument (MH) since March 21, 1983.

My visit to the Saint-Eug√®ne-Sainte-C√©cile church was an unforgettable experience. As soon as I crossed the threshold, I was struck by the beauty and serenity of the place. The neo-Gothic architecture is simply breathtaking, with its majestic vaults and colorful stained glass windows that let in soft, soothing light. The interior of the church is richly decorated, with frescoes and sculptures that tell biblical stories and scenes from the lives of the saints. I particularly appreciated the organ, whose powerful and melodious sounds resonate beautifully in the acoustics of the church. The church staff was very welcoming and ready to answer all my questions about the history and particularities of this sacred place. I also had the chance to attend a mass, which added a spiritual dimension to my visit. In summary, the Saint-Eug√®ne-Sainte-C√©cile church is a true hidden gem in the heart of Paris. Whether you are a believer or simply a lover of art and architecture, this visit is definitely worth the detour.
Very pleasant colorful church, with lots of chapels accompanied by prayers, magnificent stained glass windows and a fairly large altar.

Superb church near Grands Boulevards St Pius V and Paul VI mass according to your preferences. The priests there are very attentive and welcoming. Very accessible and many masses are offered on Sundays, morning and evening.

Magnificent church, architecture and stained glass windows of surprising precision and beauty. It is classified as a historic monument and was built in 1854 (fun fact Jules Verne got married there!) Original, neo-Gothic style with a metal structure..

Very beautiful interior which contrasts with the very simple facade. Come in, it's worth a look. Magnificent glass roof behind the choir, beautiful light through the stained glass windows, interesting ceiling ribs. It is the first church in France with a metal frame (iron and cast iron).
This church is magnificent. To visit

Don't hesitate to walk through the door of this church, the spectacle is breathtaking. The remarkable stained glass windows, the painted vaults, the columns are also painted! A true architectural marvel created under Napoleon 3 which pays homage to his uncle Eug√®ne de Beauharnais (son of Jos√©phine). The visit is really worth the detour, it's absolutely wonderful, all these colors, this incredible architecture and don't miss the organ.
